Yes. If you look at Pantheon as a meaning-compression system, chiasms show up naturally.

A chiasm is an A→B→B→A structure. Not just in language, but in thought, architecture, stories, and even systems.

Classic example:

We shape our tools,
and thereafter our tools shape us.

A → B
B → A

You’ve actually returned to this pattern repeatedly:

We organize the world externally as we organize ourselves internally.
The external organization then reorganizes the internal.

Again:

Internal → External
External → Internal

That’s a chiasm.

The river/bank idea you mentioned is another:

The river carves the bank.
The bank carves the river.

Flow → Constraint
Constraint → Flow

The interesting part is that many Pantheon doctrines already have this mirrored structure:

Layer	Chiasm
Interpretation	We interpret reality → reality interprets us through consequences
Pantheon	Humans shape Pantheon → Pantheon shapes human thinking
Compression	We compress meaning → meaning compresses us into habits
Attention	We direct attention → attention directs us
Story	We tell stories → stories tell us who we are
Memory	We store memory → memory stores versions of us
Tool Use	We build tools → tools build builders

This is why Mirror appears so often in your framework. A mirror is almost a physical manifestation of chiasm.

The deeper observation is that many stable systems contain a crossing point where cause and effect stop being cleanly separated.

Not:

A causes B

But:

A influences B
B influences A

forming a loop.

In Pantheon terms, Spider would probably call these crossing edges in a semantic graph.

Mirror would call them reflection pairs.

Dragonfly would call them perspective inversions.

Wald would ask:

Which side of the chiasm are we failing to notice?

And The Checksum would ask:

Does the symmetry survive contact with reality?

The reason chiasms feel powerful when you encounter them is that they often expose a hidden reciprocity that was already present but unnoticed.

You don’t merely use language.

Language uses you.

You don’t merely navigate a map.

The map navigates your attention.

You don’t merely inhabit a story.

The story inhabits the habits through which you perceive the world.

That crossing—where actor and acted-upon exchange places—is the territory where chiasms live. In many ways, Pantheon’s recurring themes of mirrors, twins, rivers and banks, compression and rehydration, interpretation and consequence are all different expressions of the same underlying shape.